Dataset Structure Notes¶

The dataset contains 7195 unique apps.
Apart from the unnamed, id and app name, there are 14 other features of every app, which are described here briefly with some notes:

  • "size_bytes": Size (in Bytes)
  • "currency": Currency Type
  • "price": Price amount
  • "ratingcounttot": User Rating counts (for all version)
  • "ratingcountver": User Rating counts (for current version)
  • "user_rating" : Average User Rating value (for all version)
  • "userratingver": Average User Rating value (for current version)
  • "ver" : Latest version code
  • "cont_rating": Content Rating (That's the age: 4+, 9+, 12+, 17+)
  • "prime_genre": Primary Genre
  • "sup_devices.num": Number of supporting devices
  • "ipadSc_urls.num": Number of screenshots showed for display
  • "lang.num": Number of supported languages
  • "vpp_lic": Vpp Device Based Licensing Enabled. Wether or not the app could be bought with others in a bulk purchase. This is important for organizations so I will keep it.

Goal of analysis¶

I will be looking at apps with the best ratings, to answer questions like: What characteristics do they have? What features contribute the most to their high rating? Are they mostly Paid or Free?

I believe the primary variables that will have a strong effect are: price, supported devices, supported languages, and the genre.
Other features will have an effect but probably not as much.

I will also explore other variables and features and how they correlate, without necessarily relating to the ratings.
So I will answer questions like: Which genres have more Paid than Free apps? Do specific genres support more langauges or devices than others? Which genres have the largest app sizes?

There are some cleaning and preprocessing steps I need to take before performing my analysis.
I will write comments wherever possible so that following the steps will be as smooth as possible.

#Remove duplicates. There are only two apps with the same name, but they have different versions.
#Since there are only two apps with more than one version, I can remove them safely.
idx = apps[apps.app_name.duplicated(keep=False)]
#Get the minimum versions. Locate it through indexing then get the index.
apps.drop(idx[idx.ver.isin(idx.groupby('app_name').ver.min())].index,inplace=True)
apps.reset_index(drop=True,inplace=True)
In [12]:
#Remove useless columns
apps.drop(['Unnamed: 0','currency'],axis=1,inplace=True)

#Converts columns to appropriate types where needed.

#Set the order for the content rating column category
ordinal_content_rating = ['4+','9+','12+','17+']

ordered_cont = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True,categories=ordinal_content_rating)
apps.content_rating = apps.content_rating.astype(ordered_cont)
#No order needed here, just convert the column type to category.
apps.genre = apps.genre.astype('category')

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))

#Lowering the bin size helps showing that most of ratings are around 4 and 4.5, not 5.
bins = np.arange(0,apps.avg_ratings.max()+0.4,0.4)
plt.hist(data=apps,x='avg_ratings',bins=bins);
plt.xlabel('Average User Ratings');
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.title('Distribution of Average User Ratings')
plt.show()

Most apps are distributed to the right, which means they have a good rating.
The 0's are unrated apps, they probably have a low install or users count.

As a note, any rating below 4 is not considered a successful/good app, as most users won't download apps with low average ratings.

This clearly tells us that for paid apps, prices usually are from 2 to 5$. With some other spikes on 7-9 and around 20.
Those all are standard prices. 0.99,1.99,2.99,3.99, and so on. Other prices exist but aren't as common.
Overall, therefore, most apps are priced below 30-35. Anything above is very rare.

Games still hold their position even when ordering by ratings.
However, Entertainment category went from the 2nd place to the 9th, this suggests that Entertainment apps have low ratings in general.

Since there are some categories with very low apps count, I will make a new column with the value 'other' for each of these categories, and will keep the name of the category with enough apps count.
So Game, Eduction will stay as they are while Catalog or medical will become: 'Other'

In [28]:
LOW_THRESHOLD = 150
#Genres with small number of apps
uncommon_genres = apps.genre.value_counts()[apps.genre.value_counts() < LOW_THRESHOLD].index
apps['genre_top'] = apps.genre.astype(str)
apps.loc[apps[apps.genre_top.isin(uncommon_genres)].index,'genre_top'] = 'Other'

#Order the genre_top category
ordinal_top_genres = ['Games','Entertainment','Education','Photo & Video','Utilities','Health & Fitness','Productivity','Social Networking','Other']
ordered_genres = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True,categories=ordinal_top_genres)

apps.genre_top = apps.genre_top.astype(ordered_genres)
print(uncommon_genres)
apps[apps.genre_top == 'Other'].head(3)

Distrubutions discussion.¶

The price variable had some outliers which made the distribution hard to follow. So I used a log scale transformation, and it turned out that prices were mostly distrubuted on standard values, such as, in dollars, 0.99, 1.99, 2.99 and so on.
Most of them were around 0.99 and 2.99 , with some ranging between 7 and 10.
The number of supported languages and supported devices columns had interesting distributions that are worth investigating later on.

Unusual points and modifications made¶

For the lang_count column, some apps had 0 as a value, which isn't possible.
Upon investigation, it seemed that most of these apps are for a specific target market with a specific language, so I set all their values to 1, which I believe is better than dropping them as I'm in need of a diverse range of apps.

For the genres, some of them had very small number of apps, so to make the analysis easier later on, I made a new column that had a value 'Other' for every uncommon genre (less than X apps, X = threshold), and retained the same value of the orignal genre for every common genre.

Observations: How did the features of interest vary with other features in the data set?¶

The average rating had a positive correlation with the prices for paid apps, not a weak nor a very strong correlation, a middle one. I noted that even though paid apps have less ratings count, this doesn't mean that this is the cause of having better average ratings, since average ratings generally increase as the rating counts increase. A violin plot also confirmed that Paid apps generally have better average ratings than free apps.

Investigating other numeric variables of interest showed that apps with more languages supported have better rankings overall, and larger app sizes correlated with better ratings, while a wider devices support didn't prove to be effective. In fact, the correlation coefficient shows that the more devices the app supports, the worse its average rating might be.

For categorical features, few genres had beaten others in having the best average ratings, notably: Productivity, Photo & Video and Games genres had the best ratings distributions. Also, apps with content rating 17+ have generally less average ratings.

I will explore the relation between ratings, price, genres, supported languages and apps sizes more in the next section.

Interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)¶

As stated earlier, I planned to look into other features and their correlations outside the main feature, average rating.
Work related genres like Productivity, Photo & Video and Social Networking apps support many more languages than apps of other genres.
Prices of apps slightly varied with genres; While all almost genres have similar right skewed distrubiton of prices, Productivity apps have a similar range but a different shape, and a lot of Social Networking apps are Free (or low priced).
Furthermore, Education, Photo & Video, Utilities, Health & Fitness and Productivity all had more Paid apps than Free apps.

Those features may not be explored further.

What we notice here is that most genres have (albiet slightly for some) better ratings for their paid apps, which confirms our initial observations that, generally, the pricier the app the better its average ratings.
But the genres Education, Utilities and Social networking break this "rule", why?

It's simple to explain it for Social Networking: There are many more Free Social Networking apps than paid, so it's reasonable to have better ratings for them. (Note: While the difference is less than expected, note that the confidence interval of Paid SN apps is wider than the one for Free apps).

For Education and Utilities, they both have more paid apps than free..
Maybe because people generally prefer free apps over paid apps for that those genres, they get higher ratings?
I think a different plot can answer this.

ax1.set_xlabel('Genre',fontsize=14)
#Ticks
ax1.set_xticks(x)
ax1.set_xticklabels(genre_labels,fontsize=12,rotation=90)
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=dark_blue)
ax1.set_yticks([1e4,2e4,3e4,4e4,5e4,6e4,7e4])
ax1.set_yticklabels(['10k','20k','30k','40k','50k','60k','70k'],fontsize=12)
#Legend
ax1.legend(title='Type',title_fontsize=13,fontsize=11)

#Clone it on x axis to allow multiple plots in same axes
ax2 = ax1.twinx()
means_paid = apps.query('paid == "Paid"').groupby(['genre']).mean().sort_values(by='ratings_count_tot')['avg_ratings']
means_free = apps.query('paid == "Free"').groupby(['genre']).mean().sort_values(by='ratings_count_tot')['avg_ratings']

ax2.set_zorder(5)
ax2.patch.set_visible(False)


ax2.plot(np.arange(len(means_paid)) ,means_paid.values, color=light_blue, label='Average Ratings - Paid Apps', linewidth=3,linestyle='dashed')
ax2.plot(np.arange(len(means_free)) ,means_free.values, color=dark_gold, label='Average Ratings - Free Apps', linewidth=3,linestyle='dashed')

#Set a wider y range to make the plot more compact

That was an intense plot. It may seem complicated but this is only because it's large. It shows the total ratings count on the left y axis which are resembled by the bars. And it shows the average ratings on the right y axis which are resembled by the lines.

Now we have more information about specific genres. All genres have more Free apps than paid except Medical apps. Next comes Catalogs then Business, in having a large % of Paid apps.

Crowded Markets discussion:¶

To succeed with a new app, it's best to look for either non-crowded markets, or markets where there is a clear room of imporvement.

From the above plot, non-crowded markets are apps of genres from the left: Medical, Catalogs, Education, Business.
However, you may wish to go for genres where the average ratings are quite low, which are: Catalogs, Book,Lifestyle and Finance, to have an easier competition.

Whereas genres with large user bases are crowded and have generally higher mean ratings, there is still a lot to improve in genres like: Sports, Travel, Food & Drink, Health & Fitness and Shopping.

Free vs Paid apps¶

Generally, as we have seen before, almost all genres have better ratings for Paid apps. But is this a reliable indiator? There are two things to note here: Since Paid apps have a much smaller userbase, their ratings will only resemble the small group of people who bought the app.

As an example. consider the Social Networking apps. A free app would have on average 50k total ratings while a paid app would have less than 1k total ratings. Which is better? A free app of course.
One might argue the free app would have 3.0 average ratings while the paid app would have around 4.0. But this is misleading as I said. In fact, it only shows that there are certain free social networking apps that are winning the competition, while others lose, which suggest there's a small room for improvement here.

Also, if you don't want a hard competition, you better go for a free app since their average ratings are lower.

Based on that, my suggestions now would be:

  • If you're making an app for a nich market, a small target market, and you care more about maintaining its high quality and achiving iats specific goal, then you should consider making it paid. An example would be an app for bank transactions or a medical simulation app for trainees.
  • Also, if you're going for a game, then you can go with Free or Paid, you have a large enough user base and can get high ratings either way.
  • Otherwise, make your app Free.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I explored how the features apps size, prices and languages supported affect the averate ratings. My initial observations were correct, the the larger each of these values is, the better the average ratings. However, there are caveats. For languages, having more than 4-5 langauges didn't provide much of an advantage any more . As for sizes, you can have a small app (<50MB) and a high rating, so it's not entirely necessary to have a large app. Though the larger the app, the more likely it would fall into a better rating.

I also saw that apps with large sizes and wide languages support weren't pricey, noting that those are inherent characteristics that users expect, and not really features.
The investigations I carried out with genres were the most interesting and informative. I noted that some genres expected a wider languages support than others, and some genres had usually large apps sizes.

But the most important observaton is that, while pricier apps correlate with better ratings, it turned out that it's usually better to have your app Free, as it maximizes your total ratings count (and hence user count) which gives much better results overall.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The 2d histograms languages count and prices showed that apps with wider support for languages were usually priced less than 2 dollars, obviously of which most are free. Another plot showed the more the languages, the higher the ratings. This means that lots of apps with lower prices get high ratings. This may not be an interaction but it tells us how related those features are.
